<h1>
How to help people ditch meat:
What works?
</h1>
<h3>Wednesday, June 30, 10:30-12:00 </h3>
<br>
<h4> Chairs:  Jared Piazza, PhD (Lancaster University) and Steve
Loughnan, PhD (University of Edinburgh)
</h4>
<br>
<h5>
Symposium Abstract 
</h5>
<br>
<p>
In this symposium we will hear from five presenters regarding several
promising pathways for encouraging meat reduction and curtailment,
including meat-free pledges (Piazza, Gregson), multiple categorization and
identification with animals (Loughnan), laboratory-grown meat (Krings), and
multi-level strategies (Graça). Each talk grapples with the meta-meat
question of “What works?”
</p>
<br>
<h5>Presentation 1: Pathways for enabling plant-forward transitions in
collective meal contexts. 
</h5>
<br>
<p>
Authors: João Graça, Lúcia Campos, David Guedes, and Lisa Roque.<br>
Speaker: João Graça (University of Groningen)
</p>
<br>
<h5>Abstract
</h5>
<p>
Due to their scale, reach, and nature, collective meal contexts (e.g.,
restaurants; canteens; cafeterias) offer valuable opportunities to promote
plant-forward transitions. The present work aimed to map and classify
determinants of dietary change in collective meal contexts across multiple
settings, interventions, and focal topics (e.g., F&amp;V consumption; plant-
based eating; portion sizes). A systematic review using PRISMA guidelines
was conducted in a set of databases encompassing peer-reviewed
publications from multiple fields. Articles considered for inclusion were full-
text papers reporting empirical studies on food consumption and/or
provision in collective meal contexts. A total of 27458 records (title and
abstract) were screened, 573 articles were retained for full-text screening,
and 270 full texts were subjected to data extraction. The review identified
recent trends and developments to promote dietary change across multiple
settings, interventions, and focal topics. Based on these findings, we
propose and discuss pathways for promoting plant-forward transitions in
collective meal contexts.
</p>
