<h5>Presentation 3: Investigating social support as a potential facilitator
of reduced-meat diets.
</h5>

<p>
Authors: Rebecca Gregson and Jared Piazza <br>
Speaker: Rebecca Gregson (Lancaster University) </p>
<h5>Abstract</h5>
<p>
This talk will present an experimental study currently being analysed that
tests social support as a facilitator of meat-reduction efforts. To date, over
260 participants have taken part in a two-week pledge to eat one
vegetarian meal a day – either alone, in small groups, or with their
household members. Those in the small group condition shared an MS
Teams space to facilitate social interaction. Intentions to pledge, daily food
consumption, and pledge completion rates were tracked using smartphone-
based experience-sampling. Participants also provided images of their
vegetarian meals as well as qualitative reflections on a series of motivation-
and capacity-based infographics and the barriers to pledging. Baseline,
post-intervention and two-week follow-up surveys were administered to
assess explicit and implicit attitudes towards meat. Preliminary analyses
suggest comparably high-levels of pledge adherence for our lone and
group participants, though households are still being analysed. Cost and
limited agency are highlighted as key barriers to pledging.
<br>
<h5>
Presentation 4: Two applications of intervention to meat-eating:
Categorization and identifiable victims.
</h5>
<p>
Author: Steve Loughnan <br>
Speaker: Steve Loughnan (University of Edinburgh)</p>
<h5>Abstract</h5>
<p>
In this presentation I present two new lines of research examining ways of
reducing people’s meat consumption: multiple categorization and the
identifiable victim effect. Multiple categorization has long been shown to be
an effective means of reducing prejudice and dehumanization towards
social outgroups. In the first study, my colleagues and I randomly assigned
participants to view a video which presented either a single or a multiple
categorization of pigs. We examined the impact on attitudes and beliefs
about pigs, and their subsequent pork consumption. We found effects on
beliefs about pigs but only small effects on actual consumption. In the
second study, we examined whether the identifiable victim effect – the
finding that people care more about single, identified victims than large
groups of victims – increased concerns for dairy cattle. Participants were
randomly assigned to either identifiable or statistical victims of the dairy
industry. We measured the impact on participants emotion and intention to
reduce dairy consumption. We found that although there was no direct
effect of condition on intention to consume, condition did predict
experienced distress, which in turn predicted intention. I present both
multiple categorization and the IVE as potential directions for intervention.
</p>

