<h5>Presentation 5: Having a cow and eating it too: Psychological barriers to clean meat acceptance.</h5>

<p>
Authors: Victoria Krings, Kristof Dhont, and Gordon Hodson <br>
Speaker: Victoria Krings (University of Kent) </p>

<h5>Abstract</h5>
<p>
Global demands for meat are predicted to double by the year 2050.
However, industrial factory farming at the scale needed to meet such
demands does not consider animal welfare, contributes significantly to
climate change, and poses a serious zoonotic disease risk. Yet, people are
generally unwilling to change their dietary habits surrounding meat,
especially when the alternatives are perceived as unsafe or unnatural. One
promising alternative is laboratory-grown meat, also known as clean meat,
which is structurally identical to traditional meat. Across three studies we
examined people’s perceptions of clean meat compared to traditional meat
in order to gain a better understanding of the psychological barriers to
consuming meat substitutes and analogues. The findings indicate that fear
of novel technologies used in food production and perceived safety of clean
meat significantly and negatively affect its appeal.

</p>


